{{Commons cat|Olympic Games opening ceremonies}}
{{catmain|Olympic Games ceremony}}

[[Category:Opening ceremonies]]
[[Category:Olympics|Opening ceremonies, Olympics ]]

The participation of '''women at the Olympics''' has always been below 50%. It has risen from about 10% until World War II to 45% in 2012. Certain sports that have been historically popular with women often are not included in the Olympics or are only recent additions to the games. The 2012 Olympics were the first Games in which all disciplines had both a male and a female equivalent. The Olympics made it harder to get new sports included in Olympic programme.
[[File:Women percent summer olympics.png|frame|Women participants at each [[Summer Olympic Games]] as a percentage of all participants]]
{{TOC limit|limit=3}}

==Attending the games==
In some countries like Australia, getting funding for women to participate in the Olympics during the early years of the Games was difficult.  Twenty years ago, the Australian swimming federation did not want to spend money to send female athletes to compete in the games; rather, they wanted to spend money to fund more participation of male swimmers.<ref name=HHowell-26>{{harvnb|Howell|Howell|1988|p=26}}</ref>

==Media coverage==
Historically, coverage and inclusion of women's team sports in the Olympics has been limited.<ref name="Jones-143"/> Instead, the media focuses on female athletes in non-team competitions and on team sports played equally by both genders.<ref name="Jones-143"/>

==The Games==
===Rome 1960===
The role American women at the Olympics gained in importance and visibility compared to their male American peers.<ref name=Maraniss-xiii>{{harvnb|Maraniss|2008|p=xiii}}</ref>

==Sports==
{{incomplete|section|date=July 2012}}
===Basketball===

Women's basketball has been contested in the [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] since [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976]]. {{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}

===Boxing===
Women's boxing was first introduced at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] with [[Nicola Adams]] winning the first boxing gold medal in [[Boxing at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Women's flyweight|the flyweight division]].

===Cycling===
While men's [[road cycling|road]] and [[track cycling]] have been Olympic disciplines since the first modern Olympics in Athens in 1896, there were no women's cycling events in the Olympic programme until the [[Cycling at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Games]] in Los Angeles when [[Cycling at the 1984 Summer Olympics – Women's individual road race|the first women's road race]] was held. The first track cycling event for women followed in 1988, but the 2012 London Games will be the first with equal numbers of events for men and women, which entailed a reduction in the number of men's events as well as an increase in the number of women's events. The disciplines of [[mountain biking]] and [[BMX]] were introduced in 1996 and 2008 respectively, with separate men's and women's events from the outset.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.uci.ch/Modules/BUILTIN/getObject.asp?MenuId=MTI2Mjc&ObjTypeCode=FILE&type=FILE&id=NzU5ODg&LangId=1|first=Pat|last=McQuaid|authorlink=Pat McQuaid|contribution=The equal opportunities: How to make it happen|title=5th World Conference on Women and Sport|month=February|year=2012}}</ref>

===Ice hockey===
[[File:Hayley Wickenheiser cropped.jpg|upright|thumb|Canadian [[Hayley Wickenheiser]] is the all-time leading scorer in the women's tournament<ref name=ice-hockey1>{{harvnb|The Canadian Press|2008}}</ref> and was named tournament MVP twice.<ref name=yen>{{harvnb|Yen|2008}}</ref>]]
At the [[List of IOC meetings|99th IOC Session]] in July 1992, the IOC voted to approve women's hockey as an Olympic event beginning with the [[1998 Winter Olympics]] as part of their effort to increase the number of female athletes at the Olympics.<ref name=ice-hockey1>{{harvnb|The Canadian Press|1992}}</ref> Women's hockey had not been in the programme when Nagano, Japan had won the right to host the Olympics, and the decision required approval by the Nagano Winter Olympic Organizing Committee (NWOOC). The NWOOC was initially hesitant to include the event because of the additional costs of staging the tournament and because they felt their team, which had failed to qualify for [[1992 IIHF Women's World Championship|that year's World Championships]], could not be competitive.<ref name="Agreement">{{harvnb|The New York Times|1992}}</ref> According to Glynis Peters, the [[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]]'s (CAHA) head of female hockey, "the Japanese would have to finance an entirely new sports operation to bring their team up to Olympic standards in six years, which they were also really reluctant to do."<ref name="Approval">{{harvnb|Ormsby|1992}}</ref> In November 1992, the NWOOC and IOC Coordination Committee reached an agreement to include a women's ice hockey tournament in the programme.<ref name="Agreement"/> Part of the agreement was that the tournament would be limited to six teams, and no additional facilities would be built. The CAHA also agreed to help build and train the Japanese team so that it could be more competitive.<ref name="Approval"/> The IOC had agreed that if the NWOOC had not approved the event, it would be held at the [[2002 Winter Olympics]].<ref name="Agreement"/> The format of the first tournament was similar to the men's: preliminary round-robin games followed by a medal round playoff.<ref name=ice-hockey-3>{{harvnb|sports-reference.com|2006}}</ref>

===Softball===
{{main|Softball at the Summer Olympics}}
In 1991, fast-pitch softball was selected to debut as a medal event for women-only at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]]<ref name="ISF History">{{harvnb|International Softball Federation}}</ref> The 1996 Olympics also marked a key era in the introduction of technology in softball; the IOC funded a landmark biomechanical study on pitching during the games. {{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}  The [[117th IOC Session|117th meeting]] of the [[International Olympic Committee]], held in [[Singapore]] in July 2005, voted to drop softball and [[baseball]] for the [[2012 Summer Olympic Games]].<ref name="117th session">{{harvnb|Singapore National Olympic Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/02/09/sportsline/main1300205.shtml|title=Strike 3 for Olympic Baseball|work=[[CBS News]]|date=8 May 2011|accessdate=15 August 2008|first=Lloyd|last=de Vries}}</ref> Attempts to get softball readded to the Olympic program for the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 games]] failed when the International Olympic Committee executive board instead selected golf and rugby sevens.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Stephen|title=Golf, rugby backed by IOC board for 2016 Games|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2009656175_apolyiocnewsports.html|accessdate=8 May 2011|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=23 August 2009}}</ref>  The United States have won three of the four [[Softball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic tournaments]].<ref name="Women's World Championships 2006">{{harvnb|International Softball Federation|2006}}</ref><ref name="Women's World Championships">{{harvnb|International Softball Federation|2002}}</ref>

===Weightlifting===
Women's weightlifting made its Olympic debut at the 2000 Games in Sydney, with the following weight classes:
*48&nbsp;kg
*53&nbsp;kg
*58&nbsp;kg
*63&nbsp;kg
*69&nbsp;kg
*75&nbsp;kg
*+75&nbsp;kg

==Around the world==
===Oceania===
====Australia====
[[File:Fanny Durack and Mina Wylie-1-.jpg|thumb|Fanny Durrack (left) and Mina Wylie, Australian swimmers, in 1912|alt=Two female swimmers stand on a wooden pool deck wearing bathing suits that have short sleeves and while full bodied, look like shorts go down to just above the knee]]
[[Fanny Durack]] was Australia's first female gold medalist.<ref name=HHowell-24>{{harvnb|Howell|Howell|1988|p=24}}</ref>  She earned this medal at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]],<ref name=HHowell-25>{{harvnb|Howell|Howell|1988|p=25}}</ref> where she represented a combined team of Australia and New Zealand, known as the Australasian team.<ref name="HHowell-26"/>

Participation costs for Australian athletes, costs like travel to and lodging at, early Olympic games were expected to be paid by the local sport federation sponsoring the athlete.<ref name=HHowell-26/>

In early Australian swimming history as it pertains to the Olympics, there was an attempt to prevent women from participating by male Australian swimming administrators.<ref name=HHowell-25/>

